            {
              "id": "263ae4de-12cb-38e8-b3ee-778b72620c2c",
              "name": "\"TLS Certificate Verification Disabled, Allowing MITM Attacks\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `InsecureSkipVerify` option in the `tls.Config` struct of Go's `crypto/tls` package controls whether a client verifies the server's certificate chain and host name. If `InsecureSkipVerify` is `true`, TLS accepts any certificate presented by the server and any host name in that certificate. In this mode, TLS is susceptible to man-in-the-middle attacks. This should be used only for testing.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe `InsecureSkipVerify` option should be set to `false` in production code. This ensures that the client verifies the server's certificate chain and host name. If the server's certificate is self-signed, you can add the public key to your trusted CA pool.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    InsecureSkipVerify: false,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-295: Improper Certificate Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-295",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-295"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8db8b9b3-c83f-345f-af32-2310bced1d45",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration leading to insecure default value",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `tls.Config` struct is used to configure TLS clients and servers. If the `MinVersion` field in `tls.Config` is not set, the Go runtime will default to `SSLv3.0`. This is a security vulnerability because SSLv3.0 is considered insecure and has been deprecated. An attacker can exploit this to perform a downgrade attack, forcing the connection to use the insecure SSLv3.0 protocol.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should explicitly set the `MinVersion` field in `tls.Config` to a secure value. The recommended minimum version is `tls.VersionTLS12`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs: certPool,\n    MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS12,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This is a standard library in Go, so no additional installation is required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ba8907e0-29dc-38ea-902f-e026f9af44ca",
              "name": "Insecure Default TLS Version Due to Missing `MinVersion` Configuration",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `Insecure Default TLS Version Due to Missing MinVersion Configuration` vulnerability arises when the `MinVersion` field in the `tls.Config` struct is not set. This field controls the minimum version of the TLS protocol that will be negotiated. If this field is not set, the Go TLS library will default to TLS 1.0, which is considered insecure due to known vulnerabilities.\n\nThe provided code snippet is vulnerable because it does not set the `MinVersion` field, and it also sets `InsecureSkipVerify` to `true`, which disables SSL certificate verification.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should:\n\n1. Set the `MinVersion` field to a secure version of the TLS protocol. As of the time of writing, TLS 1.2 and 1.3 are considered secure.\n\n2. Do not set `InsecureSkipVerify` to `true`. This disables SSL certificate verification, which can lead to man-in-the-middle attacks.\n\n## Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS12,\n    InsecureSkipVerify: false,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9056763d-1ea3-363c-9dc5-431ee7b8195d",
              "name": "Unsanitized User-Influenced Filename Vulnerability in Content-Disposition Header",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsanitized User-Influenced Filename Vulnerability in Content-Disposition Header\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when user-influenced data is used to construct a filename in the `Content-Disposition` HTTP header without proper sanitization. This can lead to various attacks such as HTTP response splitting, HTTP header injection, or other injection attacks.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the filename for the `Content-Disposition` header is constructed using the `node[client.NodeSpecFieldRequestedHostname]` value, which could be influenced by the user. If this value is not properly sanitized, it could lead to the mentioned attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to sanitize the user-influenced data before using it to construct the filename. This can be done by removing or encoding special characters that could be used in injection attacks, such as newlines, carriage returns, or quotes.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix using the `path` package to sanitize the filename:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"fmt\"\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"path\"\n)\n\nfunc setHeader(apiContext *http.Context, node map[string]string) {\n    filename := path.Base(node[client.NodeSpecFieldRequestedHostname])\n    apiContext.Response.Header().Set(\"Content-Disposition\", fmt.Sprintf(\"attachment; filename=%s.zip\", filename))\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `path.Base` function is used to sanitize the filename by removing any directory components.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `fmt`\n- `net/http`\n- `path`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-113: Improper Neutralization of CRLF Sequences in HTTP Headers ('HTTP Response Splitting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-113",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-113"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c2e2ae35-a64e-37d2-be2f-867f0a66930e",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure due to its vulnerability to collision attacks, where two different inputs produce the same hash output. This can lead to various security issues such as data integrity violation and unauthorized information disclosure. In Go programming language, if you are using `md5.Sum(bytes)` to generate hash values, it is recommended to replace it with a more secure hash algorithm like SHA256 or SHA3.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should replace the MD5 hash algorithm with a more secure one, such as SHA256 or SHA3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not vulnerable to collision attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the MD5 hash algorithm with SHA256 or SHA3. Here is an example of how to do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    data := []byte(\"your data\")\n    hash := sha256.Sum256(data)\n    hashString := hex.EncodeToString(hash[:])\n    fmt.Println(hashString)\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `crypto/sha256` package is used to generate a SHA256 hash of the input data. The `encoding/hex` package is used to convert the hash to a hexadecimal string.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4013543a-adfe-37df-ad12-6ee3612301a6",
              "name": "\"Possible Denial-of-Service Detection via Zip Bomb Attack: Mitigation Using `io.CopyN()`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Go programming language has a vulnerability that can lead to a Denial-of-Service (DoS) attack via a Zip Bomb. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it, because its actual size far exceeds the declared size in the archive metadata. \n\nThe vulnerability lies in the `io.Copy()` function, which is used to copy data from a source to a destination. If the source is a Zip Bomb, the function will continue to read data until the source is exhausted, potentially consuming all available system resources and causing a DoS condition.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you can use the `io.CopyN()` function instead of `io.Copy()`. The `io.CopyN()` function copies a specified number of bytes (N) from the source to the destination. By limiting the amount of data that can be read from the source, you can prevent a Zip Bomb from consuming all system resources.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is an example of how to use `io.CopyN()` to mitigate this vulnerability:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    src, _ := os.Open(\"source.zip\")\n    dst, _ := os.Create(\"destination.zip\")\n    _, err := io.CopyN(dst, src, 1024*1024) // copy only 1MB of data\n    if err != nil {\n        // handle error\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, only 1MB of data is copied from the source to the destination. If the source is a Zip Bomb, it will not be able to consume more than 1MB of system resources.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption ('Resource Exhaustion')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "19ca1c6b-42cd-3f03-a485-97ff504abf5a",
              "name": "Unintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a situation where an attacker can manipulate the control flow of a Go application, leading to unexpected behavior. This can occur when user-supplied input is used to construct a field name for reflection-based access, such as `status.FieldByName(key)`. If the `key` is controlled by the user, they can potentially access any field in the `status` object, leading to information disclosure or other unintended consequences.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it's recommended to avoid using user-supplied input to control the flow of the application, especially when using reflection. If it's necessary to use user input in this way, ensure that it's properly sanitized and validated before use. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly using the user-supplied `key` to access a field in the `status` object, validate the `key` against a list of allowed values. Here's an example of how you might do this:\n\n```go\nallowedKeys := map[string]bool{\n    \"allowedField1\": true,\n    \"allowedField2\": true,\n    // add more allowed fields here\n}\n\nif allowedKeys[key] {\n    secret = status.FieldByName(key)\n} else {\n    // handle error condition here\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `allowedKeys` is a map where the keys are the names of the fields that are allowed to be accessed. Before accessing a field in the `status` object, the code checks if the `key` is in the `allowedKeys` map. If it's not, the code doesn't attempt to access the field and instead handles the error condition.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example doesn't appear to require any specific library dependencies beyond what's included in the standard Go library.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-807: Reliance on Untrusted Inputs in a Security Decision](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/807.html)\n- [CWE-470: Use of Externally-Controlled Input to Select Classes or Code ('Unsafe Reflection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/470.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-807",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/807.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-470",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/470.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-807",
                  "CWE-470"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "60795776-203b-3216-8fa9-e404d2369133",
              "name": "Unsanitized User-Influenced Filename Vulnerability in Content-Disposition Header",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsanitized User-Influenced Filename Vulnerability in Content-Disposition Header\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when user-influenced data is used to construct a filename in the `Content-Disposition` HTTP header without proper sanitization. This can lead to various attacks such as HTTP response splitting, HTTP header injection, or other injection attacks.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when using the `Set` method of the `Header` type from the `net/http` package to set the `Content-Disposition` header with a filename that includes user-influenced data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to sanitize user-influenced data before using it to construct a filename. This can be done by removing or encoding special characters that can be used to manipulate the HTTP header or the filename.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"net/url\"\n)\n\n// ...\n\nfilename := url.PathEscape(name)\napiContext.Response.Header().Set(\"Content-Disposition\", fmt.Sprintf(\"attachment; filename=%s.zip\", filename))\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, the `PathEscape` function from the `net/url` package is used to percent-encode the user-influenced data before using it to construct the filename.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `net/http` package for the `Header` type and its `Set` method.\n- The `net/url` package for the `PathEscape` function.\n- The `fmt` package for the `Sprintf` function.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-113: Improper Neutralization of CRLF Sequences in HTTP Headers ('HTTP Response Splitting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-113",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-113"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e50671f7-9d64-3a29-87aa-d8655e15127a",
              "name": "\"Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic uses because it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, making it possible for an attacker to substitute a malicious input for a legitimate one without detection. In the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 checksum (a type of hash function) of data.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `md5.Sum` function is used to generate a unique identifier based on the current time. This could potentially be exploited if an attacker is able to predict or control the time value used as input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a more secure hash algorithm such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure against collision attacks and are suitable for most cryptographic uses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `md5.Sum` with `sha256.Sum256` or `sha3.Sum256` from the `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3` packages respectively. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    h := sha256.New()\n    h.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following Go standard library packages:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a7e7caba-28ef-3b01-b9a0-f6018219ac3c",
              "name": "Unintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a situation where an attacker can manipulate the control flow of a program. This can lead to unexpected behavior, including unauthorized access or privilege escalation. In the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the use of the `FieldByName` method, which can be exploited if an attacker can control the `key` variable.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to validate and sanitize all inputs. Avoid using user-controlled data to determine the control flow of the application. If the use of such methods is unavoidable, ensure that the application correctly handles all possible inputs.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly using the user-controlled `key` variable, validate it against a list of allowed values before using it in `FieldByName` method.\n\n```go\nallowedKeys := map[string]bool{\n    \"allowedKey1\": true,\n    \"allowedKey2\": true,\n    // add more allowed keys here\n}\n\nif _, ok := allowedKeys[key]; ok {\n    secret := clusterSecrets.FieldByName(key)\n    // rest of the code\n} else {\n    log.Println(\"Invalid key: \", key)\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the required library dependencies. However, the `FieldByName` method is a part of the `reflect` package in Go, so this package is likely to be required.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-807: Reliance on Untrusted Inputs in a Security Decision](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/807.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-807",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/807.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-807"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "04f0dd42-f63d-3836-87c4-418cba482468",
              "name": "\"Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic uses because it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, making it possible for an attacker to substitute a malicious input for a legitimate one without detection. In the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 checksum (a type of hash function) of data.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `md5.Sum` function is used to generate a unique identifier based on the current time. This could potentially be exploited if an attacker is able to predict or control the time value used as input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a more secure hash algorithm such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure against collision attacks and are suitable for most cryptographic uses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `md5.Sum` with `sha256.Sum256` or `sha3.Sum256` from the `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3` packages respectively. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    h := sha256.New()\n    h.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following Go standard library packages:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
