            {
              "id": "8a2796ec-a509-3373-85ef-778e8e62d02d",
              "name": "\"Redirect Target Vulnerability from Untrusted Request Data\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Redirect Target Vulnerability from Untrusted Request Data\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when an application uses input from an HTTP request to directly determine the location to which it should redirect the user. This can allow an attacker to craft a URL that, if clicked, may redirect a user from the intended application to an arbitrary domain of the attacker's choosing. This can lead to various attacks such as phishing and stealing of user credentials.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Redirect` function is used with untrusted input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user input to determine the redirect target without validation. If user input must be used, ensure that it is validated and sanitized before use. This can be done by checking that the URL is in a list of trusted URLs or by using a method that ensures the URL is safe.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix for the vulnerability. In this example, we assume that `trustedURLs` is a list of trusted URLs.\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"net/url\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, req *http.Request) {\n    redirectURL := req.URL.Query().Get(\"redirectURL\")\n    parsedURL, err := url.Parse(redirectURL)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, \"Invalid URL\", http.StatusBadRequest)\n        return\n    }\n\n    for _, trustedURL := range trustedURLs {\n        if parsedURL.Host == trustedURL {\n            http.Redirect(w, req, redirectURL, http.StatusFound)\n            return\n        }\n    }\n\n    http.Error(w, \"Untrusted redirect target\", http.StatusBadRequest)\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, we parse the URL from the user input and check if the host of the URL is in the list of trusted URLs. If it is, we proceed with the redirection. If it is not, we return an error.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following standard library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`\n- `net/url`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-601"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "603f40f1-f6f6-3a88-bf1a-03555e9d887f",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal a user's session cookie and impersonate them.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `false`. This means that the cookie can be transmitted over unsecured HTTP connections, which can be intercepted by attackers.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only transmitted over secure HTTPS connections. Additionally, consider setting the `HttpOnly` attribute to `true` to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, which can help prevent cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     cookieName,\n\tValue:    \"\",\n\tSecure:   true, // Set Secure to true\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tMaxAge:   -1,\n\tExpires:  cookieUnsetTimestamp,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "cecd7098-b8bc-3ff0-8567-7842ac727752",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Cookie` struct is used to create a cookie without the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields set to `true`. The `Secure` field ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted in transit. The `HttpOnly` field prevents the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, mitigating the risk of cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields to `true` when creating a cookie. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over secure connections and cannot be accessed through client-side scripts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nr.AddCookie(&http.Cookie{\n\tName:     tokens.CookieName,\n\tValue:    bearerToken,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Secure Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "614a6d0f-3ecb-3bbb-ac59-5698c811ce3c",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information such as session or cookie secrets directly into the source code. This is a security risk as it exposes the application to potential attacks if the source code is ever leaked or accessible. An attacker could use these hardcoded secrets to forge session cookies or manipulate session data, leading to unauthorized access or privilege escalation.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability could occur if sensitive data is hardcoded into the application, as shown in the provided code snippet.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use secure methods to store and retrieve this information, such as environment variables or secure configuration files. \n\nEnsure that session secrets are unique and random for each user session, and are securely stored and transmitted. \n\nImplement proper access controls and permissions to limit who can access and modify the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly into the source code, you could store it in an environment variable and retrieve it when needed. Here's how you could modify the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// Retrieve the secret from an environment variable\nsecret := os.Getenv(\"SESSION_SECRET\")\n\neDerivedSecretLocal.Data[exttokens.FieldKind] = []byte(secret)\n```\n\nIn this example, `SESSION_SECRET` is an environment variable that stores the session secret. This way, the secret is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not indicate any specific library dependencies. However, the `os` package is part of the standard library in Go and does not require any additional dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insufficient Session-ID Length](https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/latest/4-Web_Application_Security_Testing/06-Session_Management_Testing/01-Testing_for_Session_Management_Schema.html#insufficient-session-id-length)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d917a063-93c8-314d-ac6a-3b588d8842a2",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration leading to insecure default value TLS1.0",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Go programming language's `tls.Config` struct allows for the configuration of TLS clients and servers. If the `MinVersion` field is not set, the default minimum version of TLS that will be negotiated is TLS 1.0. This version of TLS is considered insecure and deprecated, and its use can expose the application to various attacks, such as BEAST, CRIME, and POODLE.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should explicitly set the `MinVersion` field to a secure version of TLS. As of the time of writing, the recommended minimum version is TLS 1.2.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can set the `MinVersion` field in your `tls.Config`:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\n// ...\n\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs:      pool,\n    Certificates: certs,\n    MinVersion:   tls.VersionTLS12,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This is a standard library in Go, so no additional installation is required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
