            {
              "id": "38540a8e-751a-37a0-8c86-9cbb0785db3d",
              "name": "Unintended Public Server Exposure due to Binding to All Interfaces",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the vulnerability \"Unintended Public Server Exposure due to Binding to All Interfaces\" occurs when a network service is unintentionally exposed to the public internet. This happens when the service binds to all network interfaces (0.0.0.0 or ::), instead of binding to localhost (127.0.0.1 or ::1). This can lead to unauthorized access to the service, data leakage, or even remote code execution.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `net.Listen(\"tcp\", \":0\")` function call binds the listener to all network interfaces, which can expose the server to the public internet.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should bind your service to localhost (127.0.0.1 or ::1) unless it is necessary for the service to be accessible from the public internet. This will ensure that the service is only accessible from the local machine.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nlistener, err := net.Listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:0\") // bind to localhost and choose any available port\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet only requires the `net` package from the standard library of Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-284: Improper Access Control](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/284.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-284",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/284.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-284"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "69605ccc-fe50-3768-a0c0-bb8581f293fb",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `false` or not set at all. The `Secure` attribute ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted by an attacker.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over secure connections. Additionally, consider setting the `HttpOnly` attribute to `true` to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, further reducing the risk of session hijacking.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     IDTokenCookie,\n\tValue:    token,\n\tSecure:   true, // Always set Secure to true\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `http` package, which is part of the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
