            {
              "id": "e2660010-12c8-3bdc-b861-36e4a7ba8b64",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information, such as session or cookie secrets, directly into the source code. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including unauthorized access and session hijacking, as an attacker who gains access to the source code can easily retrieve these secrets.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables or secure configuration files to store this information. This not only makes your application more secure, but also more flexible, as you can easily change these values without having to modify and recompile your source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly into the source code, you can retrieve it from an environment variable like so:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// ...\n\ntokenSecret.Data[\"user-id\"] = []byte(os.Getenv(\"SECRET\"))\n```\n\nIn this example, `SECRET` is an environment variable that contains the secret. You can set this variable in your environment before running your application.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not appear to require any specific library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "221c2c0e-ad39-3fd5-8409-df0b22b15002",
              "name": "\"Loading Session/Cookie Secret Material from Secret Management or Environment Instead of Hardcoding in Source Code\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the vulnerability of \"Loading Session/Cookie Secret Material from Secret Management or Environment Instead of Hardcoding in Source Code\" arises when sensitive data such as session or cookie secrets are hardcoded in the source code. This is a security risk as it exposes the secret material to anyone who has access to the source code, making it easier for attackers to gain unauthorized access to the system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to load secret material from a secure secret management system or from environment variables. This ensures that the secret material is not exposed in the source code and can be managed securely and separately from the codebase.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret material in the source code like this:\n\n```go\ntokenSecret.Data[\"enabled\"] = []byte(\"false\")\n```\n\nYou should load it from an environment variable or a secret management system. Here is an example of how to load it from an environment variable:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    tokenSecret := os.Getenv(\"TOKEN_SECRET\")\n    if tokenSecret == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"TOKEN_SECRET is not set\")\n    }\n    // Use tokenSecret\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `TOKEN_SECRET` environment variable should be set to the secret material. This way, the secret material is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A2: Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "efcb3a48-b942-3064-b6a1-b5ee16042e99",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" vulnerability refers to the situation where a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal a user's session cookie and impersonate them.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` attribute of the cookie is set to `true` only if the request is made over HTTPS or if the `Secure` attribute of the cookie object `c` is `true`. This means that if a request is made over HTTP and the `Secure` attribute of `c` is `false`, the cookie will be sent over an unsecured connection, making it vulnerable to interception.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of the cookie to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which is a secure protocol. Additionally, consider implementing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) to ensure that all communication is sent over HTTPS.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nhttp.SetCookie(w, &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     c.Name,\n\tDomain:   c.Domain,\n\tValue:    value,\n\tMaxAge:   int(maxAge.Seconds()),\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the `net/http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a7920337-90bd-38c7-b457-4aa2a387e240",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information such as secret keys, passwords, or any other secret material directly into the source code. This is a security risk as it exposes the secret material to anyone who has access to the source code. In the context of session or cookie management, this could potentially allow an attacker to forge session or cookie data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding secret keys or any other sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables or external configuration to store such information. This not only improves security but also makes your application more flexible and easier to configure in different environments.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret key in the source code, you can use an environment variable to store the secret key. Here is how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    sampleSecretKey := os.Getenv(\"SECRET_KEY\")\n    if sampleSecretKey == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"SECRET_KEY is required\")\n    }\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `os.Getenv(\"SECRET_KEY\")` fetches the value of the `SECRET_KEY` environment variable. If the `SECRET_KEY` environment variable is not set, the application will terminate with an error message.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `os` package which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secret](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ecebcf51-942f-3dbd-96af-00bfe74437ec",
              "name": "Hardcoded JWT Token Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded JWT Token Vulnerability refers to the security risk associated with hardcoding sensitive information such as JWT (JSON Web Token) secret keys directly into the source code. This is a common vulnerability in many programming languages, including Go. The risk arises from the fact that if the source code is ever exposed or falls into the wrong hands, the hardcoded secrets can be easily discovered and exploited, leading to unauthorized access and potential data breaches.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables or secure configuration files to store such information. This way, even if the source code is exposed, the sensitive information remains secure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport (\n\t\"github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go\"\n\t\"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\t// Get the secret key from environment variable\n\tsampleSecretKey := []byte(os.Getenv(\"JWT_SECRET_KEY\"))\n\ttoken := jwt.New(jwt.SigningMethodHS256)\n\ttokenString, _ := token.SignedString(sampleSecretKey)\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, the secret key is stored in an environment variable named \"JWT_SECRET_KEY\". This environment variable should be set in a secure manner outside of the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP JWT Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/JSON_Web_Token_Cheat_Sheet_for_Java.html)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2f14c82b-ac54-3c90-8a15-8757dc2a7e02",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration defaults to insecure TLS1.0, set it to a secure version like `VersionTLS13`.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `tls.Config` struct is used to configure TLS clients and servers. If the `MinVersion` field in `tls.Config` is not set, it defaults to TLS 1.0, which is considered insecure due to known vulnerabilities. This could potentially expose the application to various security risks, including man-in-the-middle attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should explicitly set the `MinVersion` field in `tls.Config` to a secure version, such as `tls.VersionTLS13`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\nconfig := &tls.Config{\n    MinVersion:         tls.VersionTLS13,\n    InsecureSkipVerify: o.insecure,\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `MinVersion` is set to `tls.VersionTLS13`, which is currently the most secure version of TLS.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not require any external library dependencies. It only requires the `crypto/tls` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2fb9ef33-8491-348d-94ce-84c24b38343d",
              "name": "Insecure SHA1 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe SHA-1 (Secure Hash Algorithm 1) is a cryptographic hash function that takes an input and produces a 160-bit (20-byte) hash value. However, it is considered to be insecure for most cryptographic functions since 2005 as it is vulnerable to collision attacks. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, leading to potential security risks.\n\nIn Go programming language, if you are using `sha1.Sum(data)` to generate a hash, it is recommended to replace it with a more secure hash function like SHA-256 or SHA3.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should replace the SHA-1 hash function with a more secure one, such as SHA-256 or SHA3. These hash functions are currently considered to be secure and are not vulnerable to collision attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the SHA-1 hash function with SHA-256 or SHA3. Here is an example of how to do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"fmt\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    data := []byte(\"your data\")\n    digest := sha256.Sum256(data)\n    fmt.Printf(\"%x\", digest)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `fmt`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f9551785-dadd-39bc-9149-a24b61caf70d",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" vulnerability refers to the situation where a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` field of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `isSecure`, which might be `false` depending on the context. If `Secure` is `false`, the cookie can be transmitted over unsecured HTTP connections, which makes it vulnerable to interception and misuse.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` field of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which provides the necessary security to prevent interception.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     CookieName,\n\tValue:    token.ObjectMeta.Name + \":\" + unhashedTokenKey,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f97832d5-e54c-33bd-a5b5-98dbd815c695",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration leading to insecure default value of TLS1.0",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `tls.Config` struct is used to configure a TLS (Transport Layer Security) client or server. The `MinVersion` field of this struct is used to specify the minimum SSL/TLS version that is acceptable. If `MinVersion` is not set, the default value is `tls.VersionTLS10` (TLS 1.0), which is considered insecure due to known vulnerabilities.\n\nNot setting the `MinVersion` field can lead to a vulnerability where an attacker can exploit these known vulnerabilities in TLS 1.0 to perform attacks such as BEAST (Browser Exploit Against SSL/TLS), CRIME (Compression Ratio Info-leak Made Easy), etc.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should explicitly set the `MinVersion` field to a secure value. The current recommendation is to use `tls.VersionTLS12` or `tls.VersionTLS13`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the provided code:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\ntransport.TLSClientConfig = &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs:    certs,\n    MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS12, // or tls.VersionTLS13\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This is a standard library in Go, used for TLS (Transport Layer Security) configuration.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b7abe607-fb7d-33ed-ae6d-089edd8806a0",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information such as session or cookie secrets directly into the source code. This can lead to serious security issues as it exposes the secret material to anyone who has access to the source code, making it easier for attackers to exploit the system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables or secure configuration files to store this information. This not only makes your application more secure, but also more flexible as you can change the secret material without having to modify and recompile the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret material directly into the source code, you can use an environment variable to store this information. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// ...\n\nsecret.Data[\"value\"] = []byte(os.Getenv(\"KUBECONFIG_SECRET\"))\n```\n\nIn this example, `KUBECONFIG_SECRET` is an environment variable that stores the secret material. You can set this environment variable in your server's configuration.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
