              "name": "\"Loading Session/Cookie Secret Material from Secret Management or Environment Instead of Hardcoding in Source Code\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, a common security vulnerability is the hardcoding of sensitive information such as session/cookie secret material directly in the source code. This is a bad practice as it exposes the sensitive information to anyone who has access to the source code. This can lead to unauthorized access, data breaches, and other security issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe recommended way to handle sensitive information is to store it in a secure environment variable or a secret management system. This way, the sensitive information is not exposed in the source code and can only be accessed through the environment or secret management system.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly in the source code:\n\n```go\nsecret.Data[\"token\"] = []byte(\"new-token-value\")\n```\n\nYou should load it from an environment variable or a secret management system:\n\n```go\ntoken := os.Getenv(\"TOKEN\")\nif token == \"\" {\n    log.Fatal(\"TOKEN environment variable not set\")\n}\nsecret.Data[\"token\"] = []byte(token)\n```\n\nIn this example, the `os` package is used to retrieve the value of the `TOKEN` environment variable.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe `os` package is part of the standard library in Go, so no additional library dependencies are required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten 2017: A2:2017-Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
