            {
              "id": "2bdcc7b6-a8f2-36b6-a280-6edae764d773",
              "name": "\"Zip Slip and Unsafe Extraction Vulnerability in Archive Extraction via External Tools (`tar`/`unzip`)\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Zip Slip\" is a widespread arbitrary file overwrite critical vulnerability, which typically results in remote command execution. It was discovered and responsibly disclosed by the Snyk Security team ahead of a public disclosure on 5th June 2018, and affects thousands of projects, including ones from HP, Amazon, Apache, Pivotal and many more. \n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when extracting files from an archive without validating that the extraction path is within the desired directory. If an attacker can control the archive's content, they can create files in arbitrary file system locations by using `..` in the file paths.\n\nThe provided code example is vulnerable because it uses the `unzip` command to extract files from an archive without validating the paths of the extracted files.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always validate file paths when extracting files from an archive. You should reject file paths that contain `..` or that resolve to a location outside of the desired directory.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple way to validate file paths in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"archive/zip\"\n    \"path/filepath\"\n    \"strings\"\n)\n\nfunc SafeExtract(input string, temp string) error {\n    r, err := zip.OpenReader(input)\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    defer r.Close()\n\n    for _, f := range r.File {\n        fpath := filepath.Join(temp, f.Name)\n\n        // Check for ZipSlip. More Info: http://bit.ly/2MsjAWE\n        if !strings.HasPrefix(fpath, filepath.Clean(temp)+string(os.PathSeparator)) {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"%s: illegal file path\", fpath)\n        }\n\n        // ... proceed to extract the file ...\n    }\n\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nThis code opens the archive, iterates over the files, and checks that each file path is within the desired directory.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `os/exec`: for executing the `unzip` command.\n- `archive/zip`: for opening the archive and iterating over the files.\n- `path/filepath`: for manipulating file paths.\n- `strings`: for checking the prefix of the file path.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A5: Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A5_2017-Broken_Access_Control)\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-22",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-22"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "47fb65bd-c48f-3eac-8a33-e881ec7c624b",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure due to its vulnerability to collision attacks, where two different inputs produce the same hash output. This can lead to various security issues such as data integrity violation and unauthorized information disclosure. In Go programming language, if you are using `md5.New()` to create a new hash, you are using the insecure MD5 hash algorithm.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nIt is recommended to use a more secure hash algorithm such as SHA256 or SHA3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not vulnerable to collision attacks. They provide a higher level of security and are recommended for most use cases.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the MD5 hash algorithm with SHA256 or SHA3. Here is an example of how to use SHA256 in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"fmt\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    h := sha256.New()\n    h.Write([]byte(\"your data\"))\n    fmt.Printf(\"%x\", h.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following standard library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `fmt`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "294b8d7d-521a-3698-8b8f-7ee4418823cc",
              "name": "Insecure gRPC Server Vulnerability due to Lack of Encryption and Credentials",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure gRPC Server Vulnerability due to Lack of Encryption and Credentials is a security vulnerability that occurs when a gRPC server is created without any form of encryption or credentials. This leaves the server open to unauthorized access and data interception. This vulnerability is particularly relevant in Go programming language where gRPC servers are often used for inter-service communication.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always use encryption and authentication when creating a gRPC server. This can be achieved by using Transport Layer Security (TLS) for encryption and token-based authentication for verifying the identity of clients.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to create a secure gRPC server with TLS and token-based authentication:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc\"\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\"\n)\n\n// Load the certificates from disk\ncert, err := tls.LoadX509KeyPair(\"server.crt\", \"server.key\")\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatalf(\"could not load server key pair: %s\", err)\n}\n\n// Create a TLS-based credential\ncreds := credentials.NewServerTLSFromCert(&cert)\n\n// Create a gRPC server object\ns.grpcServer = grpc.NewServer(grpc.Creds(creds))\n```\n\nIn this example, `server.crt` and `server.key` are the server's certificate and private key respectively. These files should be securely stored and accessible only by the server.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- google.golang.org/grpc\n- google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP gRPC Security](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/gRPC_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "47d31b31-48cc-30ce-bbf2-24ed4d1aeb90",
              "name": "\"Potential Denial-of-Service Attack Detected via Zip Bomb: Mitigation Possible by Limiting Max Bytes Read\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Go programming language has a vulnerability that can lead to a potential Denial-of-Service (DoS) attack via a Zip Bomb. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it, because its actual size far exceeds the declared size in the archive metadata. This is a form of DoS attack. The vulnerability arises when the Go program reads an archive file without limiting the maximum number of bytes read.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to limit the maximum number of bytes read from the archive file. This can be achieved by wrapping the `tarReader` with `io.LimitReader`, which effectively limits the number of bytes read to a specified limit.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to limit the maximum number of bytes read:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nconst MaxReadBytes = 1 << 20 // 1MB, adjust as needed\n\nfunc main() {\n    // Assume file and tarReader are defined elsewhere\n    var file *os.File\n    var tarReader io.Reader\n\n    limitedReader := io.LimitReader(tarReader, MaxReadBytes)\n    _, err := io.Copy(file, limitedReader)\n    if err != nil {\n        // handle error\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `io.LimitReader` is used to limit the number of bytes read from `tarReader` to `MaxReadBytes`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following Go standard library packages:\n\n- `io`\n- `os`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption ('Resource Exhaustion')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1c8ab1a9-cf4f-36d4-97f8-5c0db5fdf830",
              "name": "Unsecured HTTP Server Detected: Recommend Using 'http.ListenAndServeTLS'",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured HTTP Server Detected: Recommend Using 'http.ListenAndServeTLS'\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the use of an unsecured HTTP server for communication. This can expose sensitive information to potential attackers as the data transmitted over an unsecured HTTP server is not encrypted and can be intercepted.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use the 'http.ListenAndServeTLS' function instead of 'http.ListenAndServe'. The 'http.ListenAndServeTLS' function provides a secured HTTPS server which encrypts the data transmitted between the client and the server, thus preventing potential eavesdropping or data tampering.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the 'http.ListenAndServe' function with 'http.ListenAndServeTLS' function. You will need to provide the paths to the TLS certificate and key files as arguments to the 'http.ListenAndServeTLS' function.\n\n```go\nlog.Fatal(http.ListenAndServeTLS(profileAddress, \"cert.pem\", \"key.pem\", nil))\n```\n\nIn the above code, \"cert.pem\" and \"key.pem\" are the paths to the TLS certificate and key files respectively. You should replace these with the paths to your actual certificate and key files.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- \"log\"\n- \"net/http\"\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Go Secure Coding Practices](https://owasp.org/www-pdf-archive/GoSecureCodingPractices.pdf)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2cabb578-7052-3536-b148-def0d762ed4b",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and encode user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically handles HTML escaping to prevent XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the serialized data to the HTTP response, you should use the `html/template` package to create a safe HTML template and then execute this template with the serialized data. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"safe\").Parse(serialized)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(writer, nil)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b3b5752c-9afb-3d78-9fc4-0584d9c5b440",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and encode user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically handles HTML escaping to prevent XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the serialized data to the HTTP response, you should use the `html/template` package to create a safe HTML template and then execute this template with the serialized data. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"safe\").Parse(serialized)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(writer, nil)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "5e2fcac9-8544-3bae-9b5b-529302b117ff",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and encode user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically handles HTML escaping to prevent XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the serialized data to the HTTP response, you should use the `html/template` package to create a safe HTML template and then execute this template with the serialized data. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"safe\").Parse(serialized)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(writer, nil)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
