            {
              "id": "96d8ac44-c8d2-3dc2-ab7a-d18fcdae1b9e",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the user input will be executed by the browser.\n\nThis vulnerability can be exploited by an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or even take over the user's session.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes all data when rendering HTML templates.\n\nAdditionally, you should implement a Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict the sources from which scripts can be loaded. This can prevent the execution of injected scripts even if an XSS vulnerability is present.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the user input to the HTTP response, you should use an HTML template to render the response. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"search\").Parse(`{{.}}`)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, searchUsersGroup)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.Execute()` function automatically escapes the `searchUsersGroup` data before including it in the response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c575e4d7-1971-359d-81ab-f5c3ff530776",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, `w.Write(searchUsersAll)` is directly writing the `searchUsersAll` data to the HTTP response. If `searchUsersAll` contains user-controlled data, this could lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always HTML escape user-controlled data before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"safe\").Parse(`{{.}}`)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, searchUsersAll)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `t.Execute(w, searchUsersAll)` writes the `searchUsersAll` data to the HTTP response, but it is automatically HTML escaped by the `html/template` package.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go, used for data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
