            {
              "id": "379bf44a-13cd-3cdd-9563-dc28ea4477d2",
              "name": "Code Injection Vulnerability Detected in 'exec.Command' Input",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `exec.CommandContext` function in Go's `os/exec` package runs a command in a new process. If the command or its arguments are constructed from user-controlled input, an attacker can execute arbitrary commands on the system. This is known as a code injection vulnerability.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `r.Path` and `port` parameters are passed directly to `exec.CommandContext` without any sanitization or validation. If an attacker can control the value of `r.Path` or `port`, they can potentially execute arbitrary commands.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using user-controlled input to construct commands whenever possible. If it's necessary to use user input, you should validate and sanitize it to ensure it doesn't contain any malicious values. \n\nYou should also use the `exec.CommandContext` function's built-in support for arguments instead of concatenating user input into a single command string. This ensures that user input is always treated as a single argument, not part of the command.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere's a simple way to sanitize the `port` input:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os/exec\"\n    \"strconv\"\n)\n\n// Convert the port to an integer to ensure it's a valid port number\nportNum, err := strconv.Atoi(port)\nif err != nil {\n    // Handle error\n}\n\n// Use the integer port number when constructing the command\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(processContext, r.Path, strconv.Itoa(portNum))\n```\n\nThis code ensures that `port` is a valid integer, which prevents command injection via the `port` parameter. However, you should also validate and sanitize `r.Path` in a similar way, depending on what values are valid for `r.Path`.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Code_Injection)\n- [CWE-78: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command ('OS Command Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-78",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-78"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2a3f8487-01f3-348f-b0b0-990cbf7bd892",
              "name": "\"Potential Denial-of-Service Vulnerability through Zip Bomb Attack\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA potential Denial-of-Service (DoS) vulnerability through a Zip Bomb attack can occur in Go programming language when an application does not properly handle the decompression of zip files. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it. It is often employed to disable antivirus software, in order to create an opening for more traditional viruses.\n\nIn the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when using the `io.Copy` function to read from a `tarReader` into a `buf`. If the `tarReader` is reading from a Zip Bomb, it could potentially consume all available memory and crash the system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should limit the amount of data that can be read from a `tarReader` into a `buf`. This can be done by wrapping the `tarReader` in an `io.LimitReader`, which will stop reading from the `tarReader` after a certain amount of data has been read.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to use `io.LimitReader` to limit the amount of data read from a `tarReader`:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"archive/tar\"\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    // Open the tar file\n    f, _ := os.Open(\"file.tar\")\n    defer f.Close()\n\n    // Create a new tar reader\n    tarReader := tar.NewReader(f)\n\n    // Create a buffer to hold the data\n    buf := make([]byte, 1024)\n\n    // Wrap the tarReader in an io.LimitReader\n    limitReader := io.LimitReader(tarReader, 1024*1024) // Limit to 1MB\n\n    // Copy from the limitReader (instead of the tarReader) to the buf\n    _, err := io.Copy(buf, limitReader)\n    if err != nil {\n        // Handle error\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `archive/tar`\n- `io`\n- `os`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c6c38fe9-65e3-3e89-abeb-71f9c0cf29a5",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability due to Modification of `secret` Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability due to the modification of the `secret` variable. This vulnerability occurs when the program attempts to access or modify a memory location through a pointer that points to a `nil` or `null` value. In this case, the `secret` variable is being accessed after a potential error condition, which could lead to a nil dereference if the `secret` is `nil`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always check if a pointer is `nil` before accessing or modifying its value. This can be done by adding an additional condition to check if the `secret` variable is `nil` before accessing its `Name` property.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\nsecret, err := secretClient.Get(ctx, secretRef.Name, metav1.GetOptions{})\nif err != nil {\n\t// During the encryption key update this can fail for deleted secrets.\n\t// This manifests as an Internal Error from K8s.\n\t// In this case, we can ignore it and let a secret be created.\n\tif !apierrors.IsInternalError(err) {\n\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"could not get secret for service account: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\tif secret != nil {\n\t\tlogrus.Infof(\"internal error when getting a secret %s - not using the secret\", secret.Name)\n\t}\n\treturn nil, nil\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- `context`\n- `fmt`\n- `github.com/sirupsen/logrus`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/api/errors`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A2:2017 Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            }
          ],
          "language": "en-US",
          "contents": [
            "localizedData",
            "nonLocalizedData"
          ],
          "isComprehensive": false
        }
